A01:2021 – Broken Access Control

Description:
Broken Access Control occurs when users can access resources or perform actions beyond their intended permissions. Attackers may view, modify, or delete data belonging to other users by bypassing authorization checks.

Examples:
Accessing another user's profile by changing a URL parameter.
Viewing admin pages without proper privileges.

Impact:
Unauthorized data access
Data modification
Account takeover
A02:2021 – Cryptographic Failures

Description:
Cryptographic Failures happen when sensitive information is not adequately protected through encryption during storage or transmission.

Examples:
Passwords stored in plain text.
Sensitive data transmitted over HTTP instead of HTTPS.

Impact:
Data theft
Privacy violations
Identity fraud
A03:2021 – Injection

Description:
Injection vulnerabilities occur when untrusted user input is interpreted as commands or queries by a backend system.

Examples:
SQL Injection
Command Injection
LDAP Injection

Impact:
Database compromise
Unauthorized access
Data leakage
A04:2021 – Insecure Design

Description:
Insecure Design refers to weaknesses introduced during application design and architecture, where security requirements are not properly considered.
Examples:
Lack of rate limiting.
Missing security controls in password reset workflows.

Impact:
Business logic abuse
Unauthorized actions
Increased attack surface
A05:2021 – Security Misconfiguration

Description:
Security Misconfiguration occurs when applications, servers, or frameworks are configured insecurely.

Examples:
Default credentials enabled.
Detailed error messages exposed.
Unnecessary services running.

Impact:
Information disclosure
Unauthorized access
System compromise
